# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: powershell
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:powershell/00-introduction] Access to this page requires authorization.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] You can try signing in or changing directories.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] Before PowerShell, I began my career as an IT Pro, pointing and clicking in the GUI.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] I wrote this book to save IT Pros from themselves by reducing the learning curve and helping them avoid being reluctant to learn PowerShell.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] Instead of a book that covers topics with fictitious scenarios, this book is a condensed version targeting the specific topics that an IT Pro needs to know to succeed with PowerShell in a real-world production environment.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] It's a collection of what I wish someone had told me when I started learning PowerShell.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] I include tips, tricks, and best practices that I learned while using PowerShell since 2007.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] Each chapter includes a curated collection of links to specific help articles that expand on the information covered.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] These resources expand on the concepts discussed and broaden your understanding of PowerShell.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] This book is for anyone wanting to learn PowerShell.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] Whether you're a beginner or an experienced user, this book helps you improve your PowerShell skills.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] This book focuses on Windows PowerShell version 5.1 running on Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022 in a Microsoft Active Directory domain environment.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] However, the basic concepts apply to all versions of PowerShell running on any supported platform.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] The examples in this book were created and tested on Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022 operating systems, using Windows PowerShell version 5.1.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] If you're running a different operating system or version of PowerShell, your results might vary from the ones presented in this book.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] Robbins, a former Microsoft MVP, is the lead technical writer for Azure PowerShell at Microsoft.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] With extensive experience in PowerShell, he is a scripting, automation, and efficiency expert.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] As a lifelong learner, Mike continuously strives to improve his skills and empower others by sharing his knowledge and experience.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] When Mike's not writing documentation for Microsoft, he shares his thoughts and insights on his blog at mikefrobbins.com and interacts with his followers on Twitter @mikefrobbins.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] If you're new to PowerShell or want to ensure you have a solid foundation, start with Chapter 1.
[src:powershell/00-introduction] It covers finding and launching PowerShell, understanding versions, and setting up your environment so you can follow along with the examples throughout the rest of this book.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line interface** (**CLI**), also known as a **command-line shell**, is a means of interacting with software via commands – each formatted as a line of text.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The concept of interacting with a computer via text evolved over two decades, transitioning from physical hardware to sophisticated software.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Before the CLI, computers were programmed using physical switches or punched cards.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The shift toward a "command" style interaction began with the use of Teleprinters (Teletypes).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Early systems like the Whirlwind I (1951) at MIT began utilizing typewriter-like inputs for direct control, moving away from batch processing where you'd hand a stack of cards to an operator and wait hours for a result.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Devices like the Teletype Model 33, introduced in 1963, allowed operators to type a command and receive a printed response from the computer.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The **command-line interpreter** emerged when computers became powerful enough to handle multiple users at once, known as Time-Sharing.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS), developed in 1961 at MIT, introduced the first true command-line interpreter.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] For the first time, a user could type a command like LOGIN or PRINT, and a dedicated program (the supervisor) would parse that text and execute the corresponding function.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, Louis Pouzin introduced the software we now recognize as a "shell" for the Multics operating system, providing a programmable environment for executing scripts.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Many operating system and software development utilities provide CLI.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI enables automating programs since commands can be stored in a script file that can be used repeatedly.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A script allows its contained commands to be executed as a group (as a single program).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Alternatives to a CLI include a GUI (including the desktop metaphor such as Windows), text-based menuing (including DOS Shell and IBM AIX SMIT), and keyboard shortcuts.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Compared with a graphical user interface, a command-line interface requires fewer system resources to implement.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Since options to commands are given in a few characters in each command line, an experienced user often finds the options easier to access.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Automation of repetitive tasks is simplified by line editing and history mechanisms for storing frequently used sequences; this may extend to a scripting language that can take parameters and variable options.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line history can be kept, allowing review or repetition of commands.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line system may require paper or online manuals for the user's reference, although often a *help* option provides a concise review of the options of a command.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line environment may not provide graphical enhancements such as different fonts or extended edit windows found in a GUI.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] It may be difficult for a new user to become familiar with all the commands and options available, compared with the icons and drop-down menus of a graphical user interface, without reference to manuals.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Operating system (OS) command-line interfaces are usually distinct programs supplied with the operating system.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A program that implements such a text interface is often called a command-line interpreter, command processor, or shell.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Under most operating systems, it is possible to replace the default shell program with alternatives; examples include 4DOS for DOS, 4OS2 for OS/2, and 4NT / Take Command for Windows.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] For example, the default Windows GUI is a shell GUI named EXPLORER.EXE, as defined in the SHELL=EXPLORER.EXE line in the WIN.INI configuration file.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] This program strictly speaking is a shell GUI and by extension a shell (strictly speaking, the Windows shell is shell32.dll not explorer.exe which is a shell GUI for shell32.dll), but it is not a CLI (command-line interpreter) nor a shell CLI (shell command-line interface).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Application programs (as opposed to operating systems) may also have command-line interfaces.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Some applications support a CLI, presenting their own prompt to the user and accepting command lines.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Other programs support both a CLI and a GUI.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, a GUI is simply a wrapper around a separate CLI executable file.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, a program may provide a CLI as an optional alternative to its GUI.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs and GUIs often support different functionality.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] For example, all features of MATLAB, a numerical analysis computer program, are available via the CLI, whereas the MATLAB GUI exposes only a subset of features.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In Colossal Cave Adventure from 1975, the user uses a CLI to enter one or two words to explore a cave system.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The command-line interface evolved from a form of communication conducted by people over teleprinter (TTY) machines.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Sometimes these involved sending an order or a confirmation using telex.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Early computer systems often used a teleprinter to interact with an operator.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The mechanical teleprinter was replaced by a "glass tty", a keyboard and screen emulating the teleprinter.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] "Smart" terminals permitted additional functions, such as cursor movement over the entire screen, or local editing of data on the terminal for transmission to the computer.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] As the microcomputer revolution replaced the traditional – minicomputer + terminals – time sharing architecture, hardware terminals were replaced by terminal emulators — PC software that interpreted terminal signals sent through the PC's serial ports.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] These were typically used to interface an organization's new PC's with their existing mini- or mainframe computers, or to connect PC to PC.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Some of these PCs were running Bulletin Board System software.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Early operating system CLIs were implemented as part of resident monitor programs, and could not easily be replaced.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The first implementation of the shell as a replaceable component was part of the Multics time-sharing operating system.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In 1964, MIT Computation Center staff member Louis Pouzin developed the RUNCOM tool for executing command scripts while allowing argument substitution.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin coined the term *shell* to describe the technique of using commands like a programming language, and wrote a paper about how to implement the idea in the Multics operating system.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Pouzin returned to his native France in 1965, and the first Multics shell was developed by Glenda Schroeder.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The first Unix shell, the V6 shell, was developed by Ken Thompson in 1971 at Bell Labs and was modeled after Schroeder's Multics shell.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell was introduced in 1977 as a replacement for the V6 shell.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Although it is used as an interactive command interpreter, it was also intended as a scripting language and contains most of the features that are commonly considered to produce structured programs.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The Bourne shell led to the development of the KornShell (ksh), Almquist shell (ash), and the popular Bourne-again shell (or Bash).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Early microcomputers themselves were based on a command-line interface such as CP/M, DOS or AppleSoft BASIC.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] During the 1980s and 1990s, the introduction of the Apple Macintosh and of Microsoft Windows on PCs saw the command line interface as the primary user interface replaced by the Graphical User Interface.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The command line remained available as an alternative user interface, often used by system administrators and other advanced users for system administration, computer programming and batch processing.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In November 2006, Microsoft released version 1.0 of Windows PowerShell (formerly codenamed *Monad*), which combined features of traditional Unix shells with their proprietary object-oriented .NET Framework.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] MinGW and Cygwin are open-source packages for Windows that offer a Unix-like CLI.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Microsoft provides MKS Inc.'s ksh implementation *MKS Korn shell* for Windows through their Services for UNIX add-on.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Since 2001, the Macintosh operating system macOS has been based on a Unix-like operating system called Darwin.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] On these computers, users can access a Unix-like command-line interface by running the terminal emulator program called Terminal, which is found in the Utilities sub-folder of the Applications folder, or by remotely logging into the machine using ssh.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Z shell is the default shell for macOS; Bash, tcsh, and the KornShell are also provided.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Before macOS Catalina, Bash was the default.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A CLI is used whenever a large vocabulary of commands or queries, coupled with a wide (or arbitrary) range of options, can be entered more rapidly as text than with a pure GUI.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] This is typically the case with operating system command shells.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also used by systems with insufficient resources to support a graphical user interface.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Some computer language systems (such as Python, Forth, LISP, Rexx, and many dialects of BASIC) provide an interactive command-line mode to allow for rapid evaluation of code.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are often used by programmers and system administrators, in engineering and scientific environments, and by technically advanced personal computer users.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] CLIs are also popular among people with visual disabilities since the commands and responses can be displayed using refreshable Braille displays.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] *External* commands run executables found in separate executable files.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The command line interpreter searches for executable files with names matching the external command.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In this format, the delimiters between command-line elements are whitespace characters and the end-of-line delimiter is the newline delimiter.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] This is a widely used (but not universal) convention.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A command-line interface can generally be considered as consisting of syntax and semantics.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The *syntax* is the grammar that all commands must follow.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of operating systems, DOS and Unix each define their own set of rules that all commands must follow.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In the case of embedded systems, each vendor, such as Nortel, Juniper Networks or Cisco Systems, defines their own proprietary set of rules.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] These rules also dictate how a user navigates through the system of commands.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The *semantics* define what sort of operations are possible, on what sort of data these operations can be performed, and how the grammar represents these operations and data—the symbolic meaning in the syntax.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Two different CLIs may agree on either syntax or semantics, but it is only when they agree on both that they can be considered sufficiently similar to allow users to use both CLIs without needing to learn anything, as well as to enable re-use of scripts.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A simple CLI will display a prompt, accept a *command line* typed by the user terminated by the Enter key, then execute the specified command and provide textual display of results or error messages.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Advanced CLIs will validate, interpret and parameter-expand the command line before executing the specified command, and optionally capture or redirect its output.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Unlike a button or menu item in a GUI, a command line is typically self-documenting, stating exactly what the user wants done.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In addition, command lines usually include many defaults that can be changed to customize the results.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] These advantages mean that a user must figure out a complex command or series of commands only once, because they can be saved, to be used again.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] where *doSomething* is, in effect, a verb, *how* an adverb (for example, should the command be executed *verbosely* or *quietly*) and *toFiles* an object or objects (typically one or more files) on which the command should act.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The `>` in the third example is a redirection operator, telling the command-line interpreter to send the output of the command not to its own standard output (the screen) but to the named file.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Using `>>` will redirect the output and append it to the file.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Another redirection operator is the vertical bar (`|`), which creates a pipeline where the output of one command becomes the input to the next command.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, such as Unix-like systems or Windows, one can modify the set of available commands by modifying which paths appear in the PATH environment variable or its equivalent.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] On Unix-like systems, the file containing the executable or script for a command also needs to be given execute permission.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The directories in the path variable are searched in the order they are given.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] By re-ordering the path, one can run e.g.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] `\OS2\MDOS\E.EXE` instead of `\OS2\E.EXE`, when the default is the opposite.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Renaming of the executables also works: people often rename their favourite editor to EDIT, for example.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The command line allows one to restrict available commands, such as access to advanced internal commands.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The Windows CMD.EXE also supports restricting available commands.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Often, shareware programs will limit the range of commands, including printing a command 'your administrator has disabled running batch files' from the prompt.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Some CLIs, such as those in network routers, have a hierarchy of modes, with a different set of commands supported in each mode.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The set of commands are grouped by association with security, system, interface, etc.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In these systems the user might traverse through a series of sub-modes.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] For example, if the CLI had two modes called *interface* and *system*, the user might use the command *interface* to enter the interface mode.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] At this point, commands from the system mode may not be accessible until the user exits the interface mode and enters the system mode.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's flagship MVS operating systems, the *Authorised Program Facility* (*APF*) allows certain *authorized programs* to run with enhanced privileges, analogous to UID(0) in Unix-like systems.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] TSO/E supports calling, e.g., authorized commands, but only for those commands, programs and services in an installation controlled list.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A command prompt (or just *prompt*) is a sequence of (one or more) characters used in a command-line interface to indicate readiness to accept commands.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] It literally prompts the user to take action.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A prompt usually ends with one of the characters `$`, `%`, `#`, `:`, `>` or `-` and often includes other information, such as the path of the current working directory and the hostname.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] On many Unix and derivative systems, the prompt commonly ends in `$` or `%` if the user is a normal user, but in `#` if the user is a superuser ("root" in Unix terminology).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] On some systems, special tokens in the definition of the prompt can be used to cause external programs to be called by the command-line interpreter while displaying the prompt.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS' COMMAND.COM and in Windows NT's cmd.exe users can modify the prompt by issuing a `PROMPT` command or by directly changing the value of the corresponding `%PROMPT%` environment variable.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The default of most modern systems, the `C:\>` style is obtained, for instance, with `PROMPT $P$G`.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The default of older DOS systems, `C>` is obtained by just `PROMPT`, although on some systems this produces the newer `C:\>` style, unless used on floppy drives A: or B:; on those systems `PROMPT $N$G` can be used to override the automatic default and explicitly switch to the older style.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Many Unix systems feature the `$PS1` variable (Prompt String 1), although other variables also may affect the prompt (depending on the shell used).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In zsh the `$RPROMPT` variable controls an optional *prompt* on the right-hand side of the display.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] It is not a real prompt in that the location of text entry does not change.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] It is used to display information on the same line as the prompt, but right-justified.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In RISC OS the command prompt is a `*` symbol, and thus (OS) CLI commands are often referred to as *star commands*.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] One can also access the same commands from other command lines (such as the BBC BASIC command line), by preceding the command with a `*`.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In IBM's TSO, the command prompt is referred to as the READY prompt, after the word `READY` in the prompt.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Some shells, such as Bash, zsh, and PowerShell, allow the use of prompt systems that display a lot more information in the command prompt, like the type of remote connection, the state of machine sensors, or additional information about a version control system.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] They often use several ANSI colors, Unicode characters, and advanced shell features to set up a colorful display.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line argument** or **parameter** is an item of information provided to a program when it is started.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A program can have many command-line arguments that identify sources or destinations of information, or that alter the operation of the program.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] When a command processor is active a program is typically invoked by typing its name followed by command-line arguments (if any).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] `file.s` is a command-line argument which tells the program rm to remove the file named `file.s`.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Some programming languages, such as C, C++ and Java, allow a program to interpret the command-line arguments by handling them as string parameters in the main function.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Other languages, such as Python, expose operating system specific API (functionality) through the `sys` module, and in particular `sys.argv` for *command-line arguments*.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like operating systems, a single hyphen used in place of a file name is a special value specifying that a program should handle data coming from the standard input or send data to the standard output.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A **command-line option** or simply **option** (also known as a **flag** or **switch**) modifies the operation of a command; the effect is determined by the command's program.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Options follow the command name on the command line, separated by, e.g., commas, spaces.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Separators are not always required, such as `Dir/?` and `DIR /?` in DOS, which have the same effect of listing the DIR command's available options, whereas `dir --help` (in many versions of Unix) *does* require the option to be preceded by at least one space (and is case-sensitive).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The format of options varies widely between operating systems.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line argument parsing is used to parse the arguments of a program, and such functionality is offered in various languages.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] For example, getopt() is in the C POSIX library for parsing arguments.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In Multics, command-line options and subsystem keywords may be abbreviated.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] This idea appears to derive from the PL/I programming language, with its shortened keywords (e.g., STRG for STRINGRANGE and DCL for DECLARE).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] For example, in the Multics *forum* subsystem, the *-long_subject* parameter can be abbreviated *-lgsj*.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] It is also common for Multics commands to be abbreviated, typically corresponding to the initial letters of the words that are strung together with underscores to form command names, such as the use of *did* for *delete_iacl_dir*.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In some other systems abbreviations are automatic, such as permitting enough of the first characters of a command name to uniquely identify it (such as `SU` as an abbreviation for `SUPERUSER`) while others may have some specific abbreviations pre-programmed (e.g.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] `MD` for `MKDIR` in COMMAND.COM) or user-defined via batch scripts and aliases (e.g.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] On DOS, OS/2 and Windows, different programs called from their COMMAND.COM or CMD.EXE (or internal their commands) may use different syntax within the same operating system.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In DOS, OS/2 and Windows, the forward slash (`/`) is most prevalent, although the hyphen-minus is also sometimes used.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In some of these systems (MS-DOS/PC DOS 2.xx, DOS Plus 2.1, DR-DOS 7.02 and higher, PTS-DOS, Embedded DOS, FreeDOS and RxDOS), the setting can also be pre-configured by a SWITCHAR directive in CONFIG.SYS.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] General Software's Embedded DOS provides a SWITCH command for the same purpose, whereas 4DOS allows the setting to be changed via `SETDOS /W:n`.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Also, the current setting is reflected also in the built-in help screens.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Some versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also support a PROMPT token `$/` to display the current setting.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] COMMAND.COM since DR-DOS 7.02 also provides a pseudo-environment variable named `%/%` to allow portable batchjobs to be written.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Several external DR-DOS commands additionally support an environment variable `%SWITCHAR%` to override the system setting.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] However, many programs are hardwired to use `/` only, rather than retrieving the switch setting before parsing command-line arguments.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In Unix-like systems, the ASCII hyphen-minus begins options; the new (and GNU) convention is to use *two* hyphens then a word (e.g.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Two hyphen-minus characters without following letters (`--`) may indicate that the remaining arguments should not be treated as options, which is useful for example if a file name itself begins with a hyphen, or if further arguments are meant for an inner command (e.g., sudo).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Double hyphen-minuses are also sometimes used to prefix *long options* where more descriptive option names are used.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] This is a common feature of GNU software.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The *getopt* function and program, and the *getopts* command are usually used for parsing command-line options.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Unix command names, arguments and options are case-sensitive (except in a few examples, mainly where popular commands from other operating systems have been ported to Unix).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Conversational Monitor System (CMS) uses a single left parenthesis to separate options at the end of the command from the other arguments.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] OS/360 operator commands use a comma separated list of positional and keyword parameters; only documented command and keyword abbreviations are valid.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Keyword values are separated from the keywords with equal signs.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] TSO commands use a space separated list of positional and keyword parameters; keywords may be truncated to any unique sub-string.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Only documented command abbreviations are valid.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] One of the criticisms of a CLI is the lack of cues to the user as to the available actions.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In contrast, GUIs usually inform the user of available actions with menus, icons, or other visual cues.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] To overcome this limitation, many CLI programs display a usage message, typically when invoked with no arguments or one of `?`, `-?`, `-h`, `-H`, `/?`, `/h`, `/H`, `/Help`, `-help`, or `--help`.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] However, entering a program name without parameters in the hope that it will display usage help can be hazardous, as programs and scripts for which command line arguments are optional will execute without further notice.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Although desirable at least for the help parameter, programs may not support all option lead-in characters exemplified above.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Under DOS, where the default command-line option character can be changed from `/` to `-`, programs may query the SwitChar API in order to determine the current setting.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] So, if a program is not hardwired to support them all, a user may need to know the current setting even to be able to reliably request help.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] If the SwitChar has been changed to `-` and therefore the `/` character is accepted as an alternative path delimiter at the DOS command line, programs might misinterpret options like `/h` or `/H` as paths rather than help parameters.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] However, if given as the first or only parameter, most DOS programs will, by convention, accept it as a request for help regardless of the current SwitChar setting.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In some cases, different levels of help can be selected for a program.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Some programs supporting this allow to give a verbosity level as an optional argument to the help parameter (as in `/H:1`, `/H:2`, etc.) or they give just a short help on help parameters with question mark and a longer help screen for the other help options.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Depending on the program, additional or more specific help on accepted parameters is sometimes available by either providing the parameter in question as an argument to the help parameter or vice versa (as in `/H:W` or in `/W:?` (assuming `/W` would be another parameter supported by the program)).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In a similar fashion to the help parameter, but much less common, some programs provide additional information about themselves (like mode, status, version, author, license or contact information) when invoked with an *about* parameter like `-!`, `/!`, `-about`, or `--about`.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Since the `?` and `!` characters typically also serve other purposes at the command line, they may not be available in all scenarios, therefore, they should not be the only options to access the corresponding help information.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] If more detailed help is necessary than provided by a program's built-in internal help, many systems support a dedicated external `help *command*`" command (or similar), which accepts a command name as calling parameter and will invoke an external help system.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In addition to this, some newer versions of DR-DOS COMMAND.COM also accept a `?%` command to display a list of available built-in pseudo-environment variables.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Besides their purpose as quick help reference this can be used in batchjobs to query the facilities of the underlying command-line processor.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Notice that these characters have different meanings than when used directly in the shell.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Angle brackets may be omitted when confusing the parameter name with a literal string is not likely.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In many areas of computing, but particularly in the command line, the space character can cause problems as it has two distinct and incompatible functions: as part of a command or parameter, or as a parameter or name separator.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Unix-based operating systems minimize the use of embedded spaces to minimize the need for quotes.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In Microsoft Windows, one often has to use quotes because embedded spaces (such as in directory names) are common.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The term **command-line interpreter** is applied to computer programs designed to interpret a sequence of lines of text which may be entered by a user, read from a file or another kind of data stream.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The context of interpretation is usually one of a given operating system or programming language.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Command-line interpreters allow users to issue various commands in a very efficient (and often terse) way.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] This requires the user to know the names of the commands and their parameters, and the syntax of the language that is interpreted.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The Unix `#!` mechanism and OS/2 EXTPROC command facilitate the passing of batch files to external processors.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] One can use these mechanisms to write specific command processors for dedicated uses, and process external data files which reside in batch files.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Many graphical interfaces, such as the OS/2 Presentation Manager and early versions of Microsoft Windows use command lines to call helper programs to open documents and programs.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The commands are stored in the graphical shell or in files like the registry or the OS/2 `OS2USER.INI` file.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The earliest computers did not support interactive input/output devices, often relying on sense switches and lights to communicate with the computer operator.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] This was adequate for batch systems that ran one program at a time, often with the programmer acting as operator.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] This also had the advantage of low overhead, since lights and switches could be tested and set with one machine instruction.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Later a single system console was added to allow the operator to communicate with the system.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] From the 1960s onwards, user interaction with computers was primarily by means of command-line interfaces, initially on machines like the Teletype Model 33 ASR, but then on early CRT-based computer terminals such as the VT52.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] All of these devices were purely text based, with no ability to display graphics or pictures.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] For business application programs, text-based menus were used, but for more general interaction the command line was the interface.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Around 1964 Louis Pouzin introduced the concept and the name *shell* in Multics, building on earlier, simpler facilities in the Compatible Time-Sharing System (CTSS).
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] From the early 1970s the Unix operating system adapted the concept of a powerful command-line environment, and introduced the ability to *pipe* the output of one command in as input to another.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Unix also had the capability to save and re-run strings of commands as shell scripts which acted like custom commands.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was also the main interface for the early home computers such as the Commodore PET, Apple II and BBC Micro – almost always in the form of a BASIC interpreter.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] When more powerful business-oriented microcomputers arrived with CP/M and later DOS computers such as the IBM PC, the command line began to borrow some of the syntax and features of the Unix shells such as globbing and piping of output.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] The command line was first seriously challenged by the PARC GUI approach used in the 1983 Apple Lisa and the 1984 Apple Macintosh.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] A few computer users used GUIs such as GEOS and Windows 3.1 but the majority of IBM PC users did not replace their COMMAND.COM shell with a GUI until Windows 95 was released in 1995.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Most command-line interpreters support scripting, to various extents.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] They are, after all, interpreters of an interpreted programming language, albeit in many cases the language is unique to the particular command-line interpreter.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] They will interpret scripts, variously termed shell scripts or batch files, written in the language that they interpret.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Some command-line interpreters also incorporate the interpreter engines of other languages, such as REXX, in addition to their own, allowing the executing of scripts, in those languages, directly within the command-line interpreter itself.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] Conversely, scripting programming languages, in particular those with an eval function (such as REXX, Perl, Python, Ruby or Jython), can be used to implement command-line interpreters and filters.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] For a few operating systems, most notably DOS, such a command interpreter provides a more flexible command-line interface than the one supplied.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p01] In other cases, such a command interpreter can present a highly customised user interface employing the user interface and input/output facilities of the language.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] The command line provides an interface between programs as well as the user.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] In this sense, a command line is an alternative to a dialog box.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Editors and databases present a command line, in which alternate command processors might run.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] On the other hand, one might have options on the command line, which opens a dialog box.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] The latest version of 'Take Command' has this feature.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] DBase used a dialog box to construct command lines, which could be further edited before use.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like BASIC, diskpart, Edlin, and QBASIC all provide command-line interfaces, some of which use the system shell.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Basic is modeled on the default interface for 8-bit Intel computers.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Calculators can be run as command-line or dialog interfaces.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Emacs provides a command-line interface in the form of its minibuffer.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Commands and arguments can be entered using Emacs standard text editing support, and output is displayed in another buffer.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] There are a number of text mode games, like *Adventure* or *King's Quest 1-3*, which relied on the user typing commands at the bottom of the screen.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] One controls the character by typing commands like 'get ring' or 'look'.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] The program returns a text which describes how the character sees it, or makes the action happen.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] The text adventure *The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy*, a piece of interactive fiction based on Douglas Adams's book of the same name, is a teletype-style command-line game.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] The most notable of these interfaces is the standard streams interface, which allows the output of one command to be passed to the input of another.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Text files can serve either purpose as well.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] This provides the interfaces of piping, filters and redirection.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Under Unix, devices are files too, so the normal type of file for the shell used for stdin, stdout and stderr is a tty device file.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Another command-line interface allows a shell program to launch helper programs, either to launch documents or start a program.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] The command is processed internally by the shell, and then passed on to another program to launch the document.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] The graphical interface of Windows and OS/2 rely heavily on command lines passed through to other programs – console or graphical, which then usually process the command line without presenting a user-console.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Programs like the OS/2 E editor and some other IBM editors, can process command lines normally meant for the shell, the output being placed directly in the document window.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] A web browser's URL input field can be used as a command line.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] It can be used to *launch* web apps, access browser configuration, as well as perform a search.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Google, which has been called "the command line of the internet" will perform a domain-specific search when it detects search parameters in a known format.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] This functionality is present whether the search is triggered from a browser field or on Google's website.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] There are JavaScript libraries that help developers write command line applications for the browser as standalone Web apps or as part of bigger applications.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] An example of such a website is the CLI interface to DuckDuckGo.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] There are also web-based SSH applications that allow access to a server’s command-line interface from a browser.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] Many PC video games feature a command line interface often referred to as a console.
[src:powershell/command-line-interface-p02] It is typically used by the game developers during development and by mod developers for debugging purposes as well as for cheating or skipping parts of the game.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell is bundled with current versions of Windows and can be installed on macOS and Linux.
[src:powershell/powershell] Since Windows 10 build 14971, PowerShell replaced Command Prompt as the default command shell exposed by File Explorer.
[src:powershell/powershell] In PowerShell, administrative tasks are generally performed via *cmdlets* (pronounced *command-lets*), which are specialized .NET classes implementing a particular operation.
[src:powershell/powershell] These work by accessing data in different data stores, like the file system or Windows Registry, which are made available to PowerShell via *providers*.
[src:powershell/powershell] Third-party developers can add cmdlets and providers to PowerShell.
[src:powershell/powershell] Cmdlets may be used by scripts, which may in turn be packaged into modules.
[src:powershell/powershell] Cmdlets work in tandem with the .NET API.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell's support for .NET Remoting, WS-Management, CIM, and SSH enables administrators to perform administrative tasks on both local and remote Windows systems.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell also provides a hosting API with which the PowerShell runtime can be embedded inside other applications.
[src:powershell/powershell] These applications can then use PowerShell functionality to implement certain operations, including those exposed via the graphical interface.
[src:powershell/powershell] This capability has been used by Microsoft Exchange Server 2007 to expose its management functionality as PowerShell cmdlets and providers and implement the graphical management tools as PowerShell hosts which invoke the necessary cmdlets.
[src:powershell/powershell] Other Microsoft applications including Microsoft SQL Server 2008 also expose their management interface via PowerShell cmdlets.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell includes its own extensive, console-based help (similar to man pages in Unix shells) accessible via the `Get-Help` cmdlet.
[src:powershell/powershell] Updated local help contents can be retrieved from the Internet via the `Update-Help` cmdlet.
[src:powershell/powershell] Alternatively, help from the web can be acquired on a case-by-case basis via the `-online` switch to `Get-Help`.
[src:powershell/powershell] Shell programs, including PowerShell, trace lineage to shells in older operating systems such as MS-DOS and Xenix which exposed system functionality to the user almost exclusively via a command-line interface (CLI) – although MS-DOS 5 also came with a complementary graphical DOS Shell.
[src:powershell/powershell] The Windows 9x family came bundled with COMMAND.COM, the command-line environment of MS-DOS.
[src:powershell/powershell] The Windows NT and Windows CE families, however, came with the newer cmd.exe – a significant upgrade from COMMAND.COM.
[src:powershell/powershell] Both environments provide CLI for both internal and external commands and automation via batch files – a relatively primitive language for scripting.
[src:powershell/powershell] To address limitations of these shells – including the inability to directly use a software component exposed via COM – Microsoft introduced the Windows Script Host in 1998 with Windows 98, and its command-line based host, `cscript.exe`.
[src:powershell/powershell] It integrates with the Active Script engine and allows scripts to be written in compatible languages, such as JScript and VBScript.
[src:powershell/powershell] These scripts can use COM components directly, but it has relatively inaccessible documentation and gained a reputation as a system vulnerability vector after several high-profile computer viruses exploited weaknesses in its security provisions.
[src:powershell/powershell] Different versions of Windows provided various special-purpose command-line interpreters (such as netsh and WMIC) with their own command sets but they were not interoperable.
[src:powershell/powershell] Windows Server 2003 further attempted to improve the command-line experience but scripting support was still unsatisfactory.
[src:powershell/powershell] By the late 1990s, Intel had come to Microsoft asking for help in making Windows, which ran on Intel CPUs, a more appropriate platform to support the development of future Intel CPUs.
[src:powershell/powershell] At the time, Intel CPU development was accomplished on Sun Microsystems computers which ran Solaris (a Unix variant) on RISC-architecture CPUs.
[src:powershell/powershell] The ability to run Intel's many KornShell automation scripts on Windows was identified as a key capability.
[src:powershell/powershell] Internally, Microsoft began an effort to create a Windows port of Korn Shell, which was code-named Kermit.
[src:powershell/powershell] Intel ultimately pivoted to a Linux-based development platform that could run on Intel CPUs, rendering the Kermit project redundant.
[src:powershell/powershell] However, with a fully funded team, Microsoft program manager Jeffrey Snover realized there was an opportunity to create a more general-purpose solution to Microsoft's problem of administrative automation.
[src:powershell/powershell] By 2002, Microsoft had started to develop a new approach to command-line management, including a CLI called Monad (also known as Microsoft Shell or MSH).
[src:powershell/powershell] The ideas behind it were published in August 2002 in a white paper called the "Monad Manifesto" by its chief architect, Jeffrey Snover.
[src:powershell/powershell] In a 2017 interview, Snover explains the genesis of PowerShell, saying that he had been trying to make Unix tools available on Windows, which didn't work due to "core architectural difference[s] between Windows and Linux".
[src:powershell/powershell] Specifically, he noted that Linux considers everything a text file, whereas Windows considers everything an "API that returns structured data".
[src:powershell/powershell] They were fundamentally incompatible, which led him to take a different approach.
[src:powershell/powershell] Monad was to be a new extensible CLI with a fresh design capable of automating a range of core administrative tasks.
[src:powershell/powershell] Microsoft first demonstrated Monad publicly at the Professional Development Conference in Los Angeles in October 2003.
[src:powershell/powershell] A few months later, they opened up private beta, which eventually led to a public beta.
[src:powershell/powershell] Microsoft published the first Monad public beta release on June 17, 2005, and the Beta 2 on September 11, 2005, and Beta 3 on January 10, 2006.
[src:powershell/powershell] On April 25, 2006, two and a half years after the initial Monad announcement, Microsoft announced that Monad had been renamed **Windows PowerShell**, positioning it as a significant part of its management technology offerings.
[src:powershell/powershell] Release Candidate (RC) 1 of PowerShell was released at the same time.
[src:powershell/powershell] A significant aspect of both the name change and the RC was that this was now a component of Windows, rather than a mere add-on.
[src:powershell/powershell] The final 1.0 version was included as part of Windows Vista.
[src:powershell/powershell] Release Candidate 2 of PowerShell version 1 was released on September 26, 2006, with final release to the web on November 14, 2006.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell for earlier versions of Windows was released on January 30, 2007.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell v2.0 development began before PowerShell v1.0 shipped.
[src:powershell/powershell] During the development, Microsoft shipped three community technology previews (CTP).
[src:powershell/powershell] Microsoft made these releases available to the public.
[src:powershell/powershell] The last CTP release of Windows PowerShell v2.0 was made available in December 2008.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell v2.0 was completed and released to manufacturing in August 2009, as an integral part of Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2.
[src:powershell/powershell] Versions of PowerShell for Windows XP, Windows Server 2003, Windows Vista and Windows Server 2008 were released in October 2009 and are available for download for both 32-bit and 64-bit platforms.
[src:powershell/powershell] In an October 2009 issue of *TechNet Magazine*, Microsoft called proficiency with PowerShell "the single most important skill a Windows administrator will need in the coming years".
[src:powershell/powershell] Windows 10 shipped with Pester, a script validation suite for PowerShell.
[src:powershell/powershell] On August 18, 2016, Microsoft announced that they had made PowerShell open-source and cross-platform with support for Windows, macOS, CentOS and Ubuntu.
[src:powershell/powershell] The source code was published on GitHub.
[src:powershell/powershell] The move to open source created a second incarnation of PowerShell called "PowerShell Core", which runs on .NET Core.
[src:powershell/powershell] It is distinct from "Windows PowerShell", which runs on the full .NET Framework.
[src:powershell/powershell] Starting with version 5.1, PowerShell Core is bundled with Windows Server 2016 Nano Server.
[src:powershell/powershell] A project named *Pash*, a pun on the widely known "bash" Unix shell, has been an open-source and cross-platform reimplementation of PowerShell via the Mono framework.
[src:powershell/powershell] Pash was created by Igor Moochnick, written in C# and was released under the GNU General Public License.
[src:powershell/powershell] Pash development stalled in 2008, was restarted on GitHub in 2012, and finally ceased in 2016 when PowerShell was officially made open-source and cross-platform.
[src:powershell/powershell] A key design goal for PowerShell was to leverage the large number of APIs that already existed in Windows, Windows Management Instrumentation, .NET Framework, and other software.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell cmdlets generally wrap and expose existing functionality instead of implementing new functionality.
[src:powershell/powershell] The intent was to provide an administrator-friendly, more-consistent interface between administrators and a wide range of underlying functionality.
[src:powershell/powershell] With PowerShell, an administrator doesn't need to know .NET, WMI, or low-level API coding, and can instead focus on using the cmdlets exposed by PowerShell.
[src:powershell/powershell] In this regard, PowerShell creates little new functionality, instead focusing on making existing functionality more accessible to a particular audience.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell's developers based the core grammar of the tool on that of the POSIX 1003.2 KornShell.
[src:powershell/powershell] However, PowerShell's language was also influenced by PHP, Perl, and many other existing languages.
[src:powershell/powershell] If a command is a standalone executable program, PowerShell launches it in a separate process; if it is a cmdlet, it executes in the PowerShell process.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell provides an interactive command-line interface, where the commands can be entered and their output displayed.
[src:powershell/powershell] The user interface offers customizable tab completion.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell enables the creation of *aliases* for cmdlets, which PowerShell textually translates into invocations of the original commands.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell supports both named and positional parameters for commands.
[src:powershell/powershell] In executing a cmdlet, the job of binding the argument value to the parameter is done by PowerShell itself, but for external executables, arguments are parsed by the external executable independently of PowerShell interpretation.
[src:powershell/powershell] The PowerShell *Extended Type System* (*ETS*) is based on the .NET type system, but with extended semantics (for example, propertySets and third-party extensibility).
[src:powershell/powershell] For example, it enables the creation of different views of objects by exposing only a subset of the data fields, properties, and methods, as well as specifying custom formatting and sorting behavior.
[src:powershell/powershell] These views are mapped to the original object using XML-based configuration files.
[src:powershell/powershell] A cmdlet is a .NET class that derives either from `Cmdlet` or from `PSCmdlet`; the latter is used when it needs to interact with the PowerShell runtime.
[src:powershell/powershell] The base classes specify methods – `BeginProcessing()`, `ProcessRecord()` and `EndProcessing()` – which a cmdlet overrides to provide functionality based on the events that these functions represent.
[src:powershell/powershell] `ProcessRecord()` is called if the object receives pipeline input.
[src:powershell/powershell] If a collection of objects is piped, the method is invoked for each object in the collection.
[src:powershell/powershell] The cmdlet class must have the attribute `CmdletAttribute` which specifies the verb and the noun that make up the name of the cmdlet.
[src:powershell/powershell] A cmdlet name follows a *Verb-Noun* naming pattern, such as *Get-ChildItem*, which tends to make it self-documented.
[src:powershell/powershell] If a cmdlet receives either pipeline input or command-line parameter input, there must be a corresponding property in the class, with a mutator implementation.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell invokes the mutator with the parameter value or pipeline input, which is saved by the mutator implementation in class variables.
[src:powershell/powershell] These values are then referred to by the methods which implement the functionality.
[src:powershell/powershell] Properties that map to command-line parameters are marked by `ParameterAttribute` and are set before the call to `BeginProcessing()`.
[src:powershell/powershell] Those which map to pipeline input are also flanked by `ParameterAttribute`, but with the `ValueFromPipeline` attribute parameter set.
[src:powershell/powershell] A cmdlet can use any .NET API and may be written in any .NET language.
[src:powershell/powershell] In addition, PowerShell makes certain APIs available, such as `WriteObject()`, which is used to access PowerShell-specific functionality, such as writing objects to the pipeline.
[src:powershell/powershell] A cmdlet can use .NET a data access API directly or use the PowerShell infrastructure of *Providers*, which make data stores addressable using unique paths.
[src:powershell/powershell] Data stores are exposed using drive letters, and hierarchies within them, addressed as directories.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell ships with providers for the file system, registry, the certificate store, as well as the namespaces for command aliases, variables, and functions.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell also includes various cmdlets for managing various Windows systems, including the file system, or using Windows Management Instrumentation to control Windows components.
[src:powershell/powershell] Other applications can register cmdlets with PowerShell, thus allowing it to manage them, and, if they enclose any datastore (such as a database), they can add specific providers as well.
[src:powershell/powershell] A cmdlet can be added to the shell via modules or before v2 snap-ins.
[src:powershell/powershell] Users are not limited to the cmdlets included in the base PowerShell installation.
[src:powershell/powershell] To enable pipeline semantics, similar to the Unix pipeline, a cmdlet receives input and outputs result as objects.
[src:powershell/powershell] If a cmdlet outputs multiple objects, each object of the collection is passed through the pipeline before the next object is processed.
[src:powershell/powershell] A PowerShell pipeline enables complex logic using the pipe (`|`) operator to connect stages.
[src:powershell/powershell] However, the PowerShell pipeline differs from Unix pipelines in that stages execute *within* the PowerShell runtime rather than as a set of processes coordinated by the operating system.
[src:powershell/powershell] Additionally, structured .NET objects, rather than byte streams, are passed from one stage to the next.
[src:powershell/powershell] Using objects and executing stages within the PowerShell runtime eliminates the need to serialize data structures, or to extract them by explicitly parsing text output.
[src:powershell/powershell] An object can also encapsulate certain functions that work on the contained data, which become available to the recipient command for use.
[src:powershell/powershell] For the last cmdlet in a pipeline, PowerShell automatically pipes its output object to the `Out-Default` cmdlet, which transforms the objects into a stream of format objects and then renders those to the screen.
[src:powershell/powershell] Because a PowerShell object is a .NET object, it has a `.ToString()` method which is used to serialize object state.
[src:powershell/powershell] In addition, PowerShell allows formatting definitions to be specified, so the text representation of objects can be customized by choosing which data elements to display, and in what manner.
[src:powershell/powershell] However, in order to maintain backward compatibility, if an external executable is used in a pipeline, it receives a text stream representing the object, instead of directly integrating with the PowerShell type system.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell includes a dynamically typed language for scripting which can implement complex operations using cmdlets imperatively.
[src:powershell/powershell] The language supports variables, functions, branching (`if-then-else`), loops (`while`, `do`, `for`, and `foreach`), structured error/exception handling and closures/lambda expressions, as well as integration with .NET.
[src:powershell/powershell] Variables in PowerShell scripts are prefixed with `$`.
[src:powershell/powershell] Variables can be assigned any value, including the output of cmdlets.
[src:powershell/powershell] Strings can be enclosed either in single quotes or in double quotes: when using double quotes, variables will be expanded even if they are inside the quotation marks.
[src:powershell/powershell] Enclosing the path to a file in braces preceded by a dollar sign (as in `${C:\foo.txt}`), known as namespace variable notation, creates a reference to the contents of the file.
[src:powershell/powershell] If it is used as an L-value, anything assigned to it will be written to the file.
[src:powershell/powershell] When used as an R-value, the contents of the file will be read.
[src:powershell/powershell] If an object is assigned, it is serialized before being stored.
[src:powershell/powershell] Object members can be accessed using `.` notation, as in C# syntax.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell provides special variables, such as `$args`, which is an array of all the command-line arguments passed to a function from the command line, and `$_`, which refers to the current object in the pipeline.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell also provides arrays and associative arrays.
[src:powershell/powershell] The PowerShell language also evaluates arithmetic expressions entered on the command line immediately, and it parses common abbreviations, such as GB, MB, and KB.
[src:powershell/powershell] Using the `function` keyword, PowerShell provides for the creation of functions.
[src:powershell/powershell] However, PowerShell allows for advanced functions that support named parameters, positional parameters, switch parameters and dynamic parameters.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell allows any static .NET methods to be called by providing their namespaces enclosed in brackets (`[]`), and then using a pair of colons (`::`) to indicate the static method.
[src:powershell/powershell] There are dozens of ways to create objects in PowerShell.
[src:powershell/powershell] Once created, one can access the properties and instance methods of an object using the `.` notation.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell accepts strings, both raw and escaped.
[src:powershell/powershell] A string enclosed between single quotation marks is a raw string while a string enclosed between double quotation marks is an escaped string.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell treats straight and curly quotes as equivalent.
[src:powershell/powershell] For error handling, PowerShell provides a .NET-based exception-handling mechanism.
[src:powershell/powershell] In case of errors, objects containing information about the error (`Exception` object) are thrown, which are caught using the `try ... catch` construct (although a `trap` construct is supported as well).
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell can be configured to silently resume execution, without actually throwing the exception; this can be done either on a single command, a single session or perpetually.
[src:powershell/powershell] Scripts written using PowerShell can be made to persist across sessions in either a `.ps1` file or a `.psm1` file (the latter is used to implement a module).
[src:powershell/powershell] Later, either the entire script or individual functions in the script can be used.
[src:powershell/powershell] Scripts and functions operate analogously with cmdlets, in that they can be used as commands in pipelines, and parameters can be bound to them.
[src:powershell/powershell] Pipeline objects can be passed between functions, scripts, and cmdlets seamlessly.
[src:powershell/powershell] To prevent unintentional running of scripts, script execution is disabled by default and must be enabled explicitly.
[src:powershell/powershell] Enabling of scripts can be performed either at system, user or session level.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell scripts can be signed to verify their integrity, and are subject to Code Access Security.
[src:powershell/powershell] The PowerShell language supports binary prefix notation similar to the scientific notation supported by many programming languages in the C-family.
[src:powershell/powershell] One can also use PowerShell embedded in a management application, which uses the PowerShell runtime to implement the management functionality.
[src:powershell/powershell] For this, PowerShell provides a managed hosting API.
[src:powershell/powershell] Via the APIs, the application can instantiate a *runspace* (one instantiation of the PowerShell runtime), which runs in the application's process and is exposed as a `Runspace` object.
[src:powershell/powershell] The state of the runspace is encased in a `SessionState` object.
[src:powershell/powershell] When the runspace is created, the PowerShell runtime initializes the instantiation, including initializing the providers and enumerating the cmdlets, and updates the `SessionState` object accordingly.
[src:powershell/powershell] The Runspace then must be opened for either synchronous processing or asynchronous processing.
[src:powershell/powershell] After that it can be used to execute commands.
[src:powershell/powershell] To execute a command, a pipeline (represented by a `Pipeline` object) must be created and associated with the runspace.
[src:powershell/powershell] The pipeline object is then populated with the cmdlets that make up the pipeline.
[src:powershell/powershell] For sequential operations (as in a PowerShell script), a Pipeline object is created for each statement and nested inside another Pipeline object.
[src:powershell/powershell] The types are verified and parameters bound using reflection.
[src:powershell/powershell] Once the pipeline is set up, the host calls the `Invoke()` method to run the commands, or its asynchronous equivalent, `InvokeAsync()`.
[src:powershell/powershell] If the pipeline has the `Write-Host` cmdlet at the end of the pipeline, it writes the result onto the console screen.
[src:powershell/powershell] If not, the results are handed over to the host, which might either apply further processing or display the output itself.
[src:powershell/powershell] Microsoft Exchange Server 2007 uses the hosting APIs to provide its management GUI.
[src:powershell/powershell] Each operation exposed in the GUI is mapped to a sequence of PowerShell commands (or pipelines).
[src:powershell/powershell] The host creates the pipeline and executes them.
[src:powershell/powershell] In fact, the interactive PowerShell console itself is a PowerShell host, which interprets the scripts entered at command line and creates the necessary `Pipeline` objects and invokes them.
[src:powershell/powershell] DSC allows for declaratively specifying how a software environment should be configured.
[src:powershell/powershell] Upon running a *configuration*, DSC will ensure that the system gets the state described in the configuration.
[src:powershell/powershell] The *Local Configuration Manager* (LCM) periodically polls the system using the control flow described by *resources* (imperative pieces of DSC) to make sure that the state of a configuration is maintained.
[src:powershell/powershell] All major releases are still supported, and each major release has featured backwards compatibility with preceding versions.
[src:powershell/powershell] Initially using the code name "Monad", PowerShell was first shown publicly at the Professional Developers Conference in October 2003 in Los Angeles.
[src:powershell/powershell] Named Windows PowerShell, version 1.0 was released in November 2006 for Windows XP SP2, Windows Server 2003 SP1 and Windows Vista and as an optional component of Windows Server 2008.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 2.0 integrates with Windows 7 and Windows Server 2008 R2 and is released for Windows XP with Service Pack 3, Windows Server 2003 with Service Pack 2, and Windows Vista with Service Pack 1.
[src:powershell/powershell] The version includes changes to the language and hosting API, in addition to including more than 240 new cmdlets.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 3.0 integrates with Windows 8, Windows Server 2012, Windows 7 with Service Pack 1, Windows Server 2008 with Service Pack 1, and Windows Server 2008 R2 with Service Pack 1.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 3.0 is part of a larger package, Windows Management Framework 3.0 (WMF3), which also contains the WinRM service to support remoting.
[src:powershell/powershell] Microsoft made several Community Technology Preview releases of WMF3.
[src:powershell/powershell] An early community technology preview 2 (CTP 2) version of Windows Management Framework 3.0 was released on December 2, 2011.
[src:powershell/powershell] Windows Management Framework 3.0 was released for general availability in December 2012 and is included with Windows 8 and Windows Server 2012 by default.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 4.0 integrates with Windows 8.1, Windows Server 2012 R2, Windows 7 SP1, Windows Server 2008 R2 SP1 and Windows Server 2012.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 5.0 was re-released with Windows Management Framework (WMF) 5.0 on February 24, 2016, following an initial release with a severe bug.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 5.1 was released along with the Windows 10 Anniversary Update on August 2, 2016, and in Windows Server 2016.
[src:powershell/powershell] PackageManagement now supports proxies, PSReadLine now has ViMode support, and two new cmdlets were added: Get-TimeZone and Set-TimeZone.
[src:powershell/powershell] The LocalAccounts module allows for adding/removing local user accounts.
[src:powershell/powershell] A preview for was released for Windows 7, Windows Server 2008, Windows Server 2008 R2, Windows Server 2012, and Windows Server 2012 R2 on July 16, 2016, and was released on January 19, 2017.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 5.1 is the first to come in two editions of "Desktop" and "Core".
[src:powershell/powershell] The "Desktop" edition is the continuation product line that uses the .NET Framework, and the "Core" edition runs on .NET Core and is bundled with Windows Server 2016 Nano Server.
[src:powershell/powershell] In exchange for smaller footprint, the latter lacks some features such as the cmdlets to manage clipboard or join a computer to a domain, WMI version 1 cmdlets, Event Log cmdlets and profiles.
[src:powershell/powershell] This was the final version exclusively for Windows.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 5.1 remains pre-installed on Windows 10, Windows 11 and Windows Server 2022, while the .NET version needs to be installed separately and can run side-by-side with the .NET Framework version.
[src:powershell/powershell] Renamed to PowerShell Core, version 6.0 was first announced on August 18, 2016, when Microsoft unveiled its decision to make the product cross-platform, independent of Windows, free and open source.
[src:powershell/powershell] It achieved general availability on January 10, 2018, for Windows, macOS and Linux.
[src:powershell/powershell] It has its own support lifecycle and adheres to the Microsoft lifecycle policy that is introduced with Windows 10: Only the latest version of PowerShell Core is supported.
[src:powershell/powershell] Microsoft expects to release one minor version for PowerShell Core 6.0 every six months.
[src:powershell/powershell] The most significant change in this version is the expansion to the other platforms.
[src:powershell/powershell] For Windows administrators, this version did not include any major new features.
[src:powershell/powershell] In an interview with the community on January 11, 2018, the development team was asked to list the top 10 most exciting things that would happen for a Windows IT professional who would migrate from version 5.1 to version 6.0.
[src:powershell/powershell] In response, Angel Calvo of Microsoft could only name two: cross-platform and open-source.
[src:powershell/powershell] PowerShell 6 changed to UTF-8 as default encoding, with some exceptions.
[src:powershell/powershell] According to Microsoft, one of the new features of version 6.1 is "Compatibility with 1900+ existing cmdlets in Windows 10 and Windows Server 2019." Still, no details of these cmdlets can be found in the full version of the change log.
[src:powershell/powershell] Microsoft later professes that this number was insufficient as PowerShell Core failed to replace Windows PowerShell 5.1 and gain traction on Windows.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 6.2 is focused primarily on performance improvements, bug fixes, and smaller cmdlet and language enhancements that improved developer productivity.
[src:powershell/powershell] Renamed to simply PowerShell, version 7 replaces the previous product lines: PowerShell Core and Windows PowerShell.
[src:powershell/powershell] The focus in development was to make version 7 a viable replacement for version 5.1, i.e. to have near parity with it in terms of compatibility with modules that ship with Windows.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 7.2 is the next long-term support version, after version 7.0.
[src:powershell/powershell] It uses .NET 6.0 and features universal installer packages for Linux.
[src:powershell/powershell] On Windows, updates to version 7.2 and later come via the Microsoft Update service; this feature has been missing from versions 6.0 through 7.1.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 7.3 includes some general Cmdlet updates and fixes, testing for framework dependent package in release pipeline as well as build and packaging improvements.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 7.4 is based on .NET 8 and is considered the long term support (LTS) release.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 7.5 is the latest stable release, released January 2025; it was built on .NET 9.0.1.
[src:powershell/powershell] It includes enhancements for performance, usability, and security.
[src:powershell/powershell] Key updates include improvements to tab completion, such as better type inference and new argument completers, as well as fixes for Invoke-WebRequest and Invoke-RestMethod.
[src:powershell/powershell] This release also adds the new ConvertTo-CliXml and ConvertFrom-CliXml cmdlets, and updates core modules like PSReadLine and Microsoft.PowerShell.PSResourceGet.
[src:powershell/powershell] Breaking changes include updates to Test-Path parameter handling, and default settings for New-FileCatalog.
[src:powershell/powershell] Prior to GA Release there were 5 preview releases and 1 RC release of PowerShell v7.5.0, with a full release blog post for this version expected soon.
[src:powershell/powershell] Version 7.6 is based on .NET 9 and is the latest release.
[src:powershell/powershell] The following table contains various cmdlets that ship with PowerShell that have notably similar functionality to commands in other shells.
[src:powershell/powershell] Many of these cmdlets are exposed to the user via predefined aliases to make their use familiar to users of the other shells.
[src:powershell/powershell] *fc* is defined in the POSIX standard and **history** is not.
[src:powershell/powershell] However most Unix implementations also define **history**.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] In computing, a **script** is a relatively short and simple set of instructions that typically automate an otherwise manual process.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] The act of writing a script is called **scripting**.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A **scripting language** or **script language** is a programming language that is used for scripting.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Originally, scripting was limited to automating shells in operating systems, and languages were relatively simple.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Today, scripting is more pervasive and some scripting languages include modern features that allow them to be used to develop application software also.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A scripting language can be a general-purpose programming language or a domain-specific language for a given environment.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] When embedded in an application, it may be called an *extension language*.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A scripting language is sometimes referred to as very high-level programming language if it operates at a high level of abstraction, or as a *control language*, especially for job control languages on mainframe computers.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] The term *scripting language* is sometimes used in a wider sense, to refer to dynamic high-level programming languages in general.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Some are strictly interpreted languages, while others use a form of compilation.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] In this context, the term *script* refers to a small program in such a language.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Typically, a script is contained in a single file, and no larger than a few thousand lines of code.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] The scope of scripting languages ranges from small to large, and from highly domain-specific language to general-purpose programming languages.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A language may start as small and highly domain-specific and later develop into a portable and general-purpose language; conversely, a general-purpose language may later develop special domain-specific dialects.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Script is a subjective characterization that generally includes the following attributes.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A script is usually not compiled, at least not its usual meaning.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Generally, they are interpreted directly from source code, or from bytecode, or run as native after just-in-time compilation.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A script is generally relatively short and simple.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] As there is no limit on size or complexity, script is subjective.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A few lines of code without branching is probably considered a script.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A codebase of multiple files, that performs sophisticated user or hardware interface or complicated algorithms or multiprogramming is probably not considered a script.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A script usually automates a task that would otherwise be performed by a person in a more manual way.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A language that is primarily intended for scripting generally has limited capabilities compared to a general-purpose language.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A scripting language may lack the functionality to write complex applications.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Typically, a script starts executing at the first line of code whereas an application typically starts at a special point in the code called the entry point.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] For example, Java is not script-like since an application starts at the function named `main` which need not be at the top of the code.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] The following code starts at `main`, then calls `printHelloWorld` which prints "Hello World".
[src:powershell/scripting-language] In contrast, the following Python code prints "Hello World" without the `main` function or other syntax such as a class definition required by Java.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Scripts are often created or modified by the person executing them, but they are also often distributed, such as when large portions of games are written in a scripting language, notably the Google Chrome T-rex game.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Early mainframe computers (in the 1950s) were non-interactive, instead using batch processing.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] IBM's Job Control Language (JCL) is the archetype of languages used to control batch processing.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] The first interactive shells were developed in the 1960s to enable remote operation of the first time-sharing systems, and these used shell scripts, which controlled running computer programs within a computer program, the shell.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Calvin Mooers in his TRAC language is generally credited with inventing *command substitution*, the ability to embed commands in scripts that, when interpreted, insert a character string into the script.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Louis Pouzin wrote an early processor for command scripts called RUNCOM for CTSS around 1964.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Stuart Madnick at MIT wrote a scripting language for IBM's CP/CMS in 1966.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] He originally called this processor COMMAND, later named EXEC.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Multics included an offshoot of CTSS RUNCOM, also called RUNCOM.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] EXEC was eventually replaced by EXEC 2 and Rexx.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Languages such as Tcl and Lua were specifically designed as general-purpose scripting languages that could be embedded in any application.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Other languages such as Visual Basic for Applications (VBA) provided strong integration with the automation facilities of an underlying system.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Embedding of such general-purpose scripting languages instead of developing a new language for each application also had obvious benefits, relieving the application developer of the need to code a language translator from scratch and allowing the user to apply skills learned elsewhere.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Some software incorporates several different scripting languages.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Modern web browsers typically provide a language for writing extensions to the browser itself, and several standard embedded languages for controlling the browser, including JavaScript (a dialect of ECMAScript) or XUL.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Scripting languages can be categorized into several different types, with a considerable degree of overlap among the types.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Scripting is often contrasted with system programming, as in Ousterhout's dichotomy or "programming in the large and programming in the small".
[src:powershell/scripting-language] In this view, scripting is glue code, connecting software components, and a language specialized for this purpose is a *glue language*.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Pipelines and shell scripting are archetypal examples of glue languages, and Perl was initially developed to fill this same role.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Web development can be considered a use of glue languages, interfacing between a database and web server.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] But if a substantial amount of logic is written in script, it is better characterized as simply another software component, not "glue".
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Macro languages exposed to operating system or application components can serve as glue languages.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] These include Visual Basic for Applications, WordBasic, LotusScript, CorelScript, Hummingbird Basic, QuickScript, Rexx, SaxBasic, and WinWrap Basic.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Other tools like AWK can also be considered glue languages, as can any language implemented by a Windows Script Host engine (VBScript, JScript and VBA by default in Windows and third-party engines including implementations of Rexx, Perl, Tcl, Python, XSLT, Ruby, Modern Pascal, Delphi, and C).
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A majority of applications can access and use operating system components via the object models or its own functions.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Depending upon the OS version, WSH and the default script engines (VBScript and JScript) are available.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Programmable calculators can be programmed in glue languages in three ways.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] For example, the Texas Instruments TI-92, by factory default can be programmed with a command script language.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Inclusion of the scripting and glue language Lua in the TI-NSpire series of calculators could be seen as a successor to this.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] The primary on-board high-level programming languages of most graphing calculators (most often Basic variants, sometimes Lisp derivatives, and more uncommonly, C derivatives) in many cases can glue together calculator functions—such as graphs, lists, matrices, etc.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Third-party implementations of more comprehensive Basic version that may be closer to variants listed as glue languages in this article are available—and attempts to implement Perl, Rexx, or various operating system shells on the TI and HP graphing calculators are also mentioned.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A number of text editors support macros written either using a macro language built into the editor, e.g., The SemWare Editor (TSE), vi improved (VIM), or using an external implementation, e.g., XEDIT, or both, e.g., KEDIT.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Sometimes text editors and edit macros are used under the covers to provide other applications, e.g., FILELIST and RDRLIST in CMS .
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Many of these languages' interpreters double as command-line interpreters such as the Unix shell or the MS-DOS `COMMAND.COM`.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Others, such as AppleScript offer the use of English-like commands to build scripts.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] With the advent of graphical user interfaces, a specialized kind of scripting language emerged for controlling a computer.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] These languages interact with the same graphic windows, menus, buttons, and so on, that a human user would.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] They do this by simulating the actions of a user.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] These languages are typically used to automate user actions.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Such languages are also called *macros* when control is through simulated key presses or mouse clicks, and tapping or pressing on a touch-activated screen.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] These languages could in principle be used to control any GUI application, but in practice their use is limited because they need support from the application and from the operating system.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] There are a few exceptions to this limit.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Some GUI scripting languages are based on recognizing graphical objects from their display screen pixels.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] These GUI scripting languages do not depend on support from the operating system or application.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] When the GUI provides the appropriate interfaces, as in the IBM Workplace Shell, a generic scripting language, e.g., Object REXX, can be used to write GUI scripts.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Likewise, many computer game systems use a custom scripting language to express the programmed actions of non-player characters and the game environment.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Languages of this sort are designed for a single application; while they may superficially resemble a specific general-purpose language (e.g., QuakeC, modeled after C), they have custom features that distinguish them.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Emacs Lisp, while a fully formed and capable dialect of Lisp, contains many special features that make it most useful for extending the editing functions of Emacs.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] An application-specific scripting language can be viewed as a domain-specific programming language specialized to one application.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A number of languages have been designed for the purpose of replacing application-specific scripting languages by being embeddable in application programs.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] The application programmer (working in C or another systems language) includes "hooks" where the scripting language can control the application.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] These languages may be technically equivalent to an application-specific extension language but when an application embeds a "common" language, the user gets the advantage of being able to transfer skills from application to application.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] A more generic alternative is simply to provide a library (often a C library) that a general-purpose language can use to control the application, without modifying the language for the specific domain.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] JavaScript began as, and still is mostly, a language for scripting inside web browsers.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] However, the standardizing of the language as ECMAScript has made it popular as a general-purpose embeddable language.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] The Mozilla implementation SpiderMonkey is embedded in several environments such as the Yahoo Widgets Engine,and applications such as the Adobe products Flash (ActionScript) and Acrobat (for scripting PDF files).
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Tcl was created as an extension language but has come to be used more often as a general-purpose language in roles similar to Python, Perl, and Ruby.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] In contrast, Rexx was created as a job control language, but is widely used as an extension language and a general-purpose language.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Perl is a general-purpose language, but had the Oraperl (1990) dialect, consisting of a Perl 4 binary with Oracle Call Interface compiled in.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] This has however since been replaced by a library (Perl Module), DBD::Oracle.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Other complex and task-oriented applications may incorporate and expose an embedded programming language to allow their users more control and give them more functionality than can be available through a user interface, no matter how sophisticated.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] For example, Autodesk Maya 3D authoring tools embed the Maya Embedded Language, or Blender which uses Python to fill this role.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] Some other types of applications that need faster feature addition or tweak-and-run cycles (e.g. game engines) also use an embedded language.
[src:powershell/scripting-language] During the development, this allows them to prototype features faster and tweak more freely, without the need for the user to have intimate knowledge of the inner workings of the application or to rebuild it after each tweak (which can take a significant amount of time).
[src:powershell/scripting-language] The scripting languages used for this purpose range from the more common and more famous Lua and Python to lesser-known ones such as AngelScript and Squirrel.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] PowerShell is a cross-platform task automation solution made up of a command-line shell, a scripting language, and a configuration management framework.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] PowerShell runs on Windows, Linux, and macOS.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] PowerShell is a modern command shell that includes the best features of other popular shells.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] Unlike most shells that only accept and return text, PowerShell accepts and returns .NET objects.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] As a scripting language, PowerShell is commonly used for automating the management of systems.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] It's also used to build, test, and deploy solutions, often in CI/CD environments.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] PowerShell is built on the .NET Common Language Runtime (CLR).
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] All inputs and outputs are .NET objects.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] No need to parse text output to extract information from output.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] The extensible nature of PowerShell provides an ecosystem of PowerShell modules to deploy and manage almost any technology you work with.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] PowerShell Desired State Configuration (DSC) is a management framework in PowerShell that enables you to manage your enterprise infrastructure with configuration as code.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] Jeffrey Snover, the inventor of PowerShell, wrote the Monad Manifesto to explain his vision for PowerShell and how it would change the way we manage systems.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] Use the following link to download a copy of the Monad Manifesto.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] This PDF file is a version of the original Monad Manifesto, which articulated the long-term vision and started the development effort that became PowerShell.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] PowerShell has delivered on many of the elements described in this document.
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] Are you new to PowerShell and don't know where to start?
[src:powershell/scripting-overview] Take a look at how PowerShell is being used in different scenarios and on different platforms.
